    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Susan P. Wright received her B.A. in Physics from Oxford University in 1961. She went on to earn an M.S. degree in Physics from the University of Michigan in 1963 and a Ph.D. degree in History of Science from Harvard University in 1975. She joined the University of Michigan Faculty as a lecturer in 1979 and received an additional appointment as associate research scientist in 1998 with promotion to research scientist in 2002. Wright founded the Residential College's Science, Technology, and Society Program in 1979 and chaired it until 1997. The program combines science training with the study of its relationship to society and culture. Her work in the Institute for Research on Women and Gender focused on rethinking approaches to arms control and disarmament. She was especially involved in research on national and international policies guiding the development of biotechnology. In 1998-1999, she directed an international project on biological warfare and disarmament. Dr. Wright received numerous awards, including the Rockefeller Humanities Fellowship, the MacArthur Research and Writing Fellowship, and the University of Michigan Excellence in Education Award. She retired from active faculty status in 2005 and was named lecturer and research scientist emerita.</p>
      <p>Source: Proceedings of the University of Michigan Board of Regents, October 2005.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Susan Wright Papers document the recombinant DNA debate at the University of Michigan during the 1970s and early 1980s through material collected by Dr. Wright. In the early 1970s, scientists discovered a method to combine DNA from different organisms, creating DNA sequences not found in nature. This led to concern that, among other things, the organisms possessing this recombined DNA could escape from laboratories and cause pandemics. A debate over how much this new technology should be regulated by the government ensued. Wright was involved in this debate through her position as chair of the Residential College's Science, Technology, and Society Program. The papers are arranged into four series: Ann Arbor Newspaper Coverage, Correspondence, Minutes, and Articles, Governor's Task Force, and Topical.</p>
    </scopecontent>
